[1
Date: 27 Nov 2000
From: Schildorfer Hermann <schildorfer@batsb.at>

Spongiform Encephalitis (BSE) in Europe / Austria (based on information
via radio and TV). The EC (European Community) is actually discussing
the introduction of obligatory checks of all animals slaughtered.>
The EC TSE-surveillance program [European Community Transmissible
Spongiform Encephalopathy according to the decision of the Commission
98/272/EC will be continued in the year 2001 in the form amended by the
decision of the Commission 2000/374/EC.
This surveillance will include testing of slaughtered sick cattle and
fallen stock. Austria will transpose this decision, and will also do
other testing (for instance on imported animals from countries which had
cases of BSE).
countries where the occurrence of BSE has been proven, but should be
mandatory in all countries of the EC.
Austria, which has never had a case of BSE (nor a case of scrapie),
stopped using bonemeal and other animal parts for feeding cattle in 1991
and has given the order to check every animal with symptoms similar to
those of "mad cow disease" for BSE.>
Austria never had a case of BSE but had its a first case of scrapie
earlier this year.
Austria had a special situation since the end of WW II which made soybean
meal very cheap. Because of this reason it was not useful to feed MBM to
ruminants, after the appearance of BSE it was banned officially too.
Rendering plants in Austria had to use steam autoclaving (134 C) long
before the BSE crisis happened and never changed this.
--
Hermann Schildorfer, DVM
Head of Austrian Reference Laboratory for animal TSE
<schildorfer@batsb.at
