[2
Date: 27 Nov 2000
From: Stefan Brockmann <Brockmann@lga.bwl.de
Source: Associated Press, 25 Nov 2000 [edited

The German Ministry of Agriculture stated Saturday 25 Nov 2000, after a
meeting of the "bund-laender BSE crisis commission" feeding of animals on
bone meal will be illegal in Germany, beginning Wednesday 29 Nov 2000.
The first case of BSE was confirmed by the national reference center in
Tuebingen. The Government of the State of Schleswig Holstein, were the
suspected cow was stabled, has arranged a BSE hotline.
Furthermore the press reports the first suspected case of nvCJD, a 22
year old male Bavarian patient, suffering from progression of the disease
for 18 months. The head of the Division of Neuropathology at the Munich
"Klinikum GroDFhadern", Hans Kretzschmar, could not confirm nor deny
nvCJD or sporadic form of the disease.
*********
[3
Date: 27 Nov 2000
From: H. Larry Penning, M.D. <hlpenning@yahoo.com>
Source: Reuters, 27 Nov 2000 [edited
BERLIN - Germany authorities said a backup test confirmed the country's
first case of BSE, as anger grew towards those who had insisted the
country would remain free of the brain-wasting illness.
Heide Simonis, state premier of the northern region of
Schleswig-Holstein, said a second test by federal health authorities
confirmed the results of an earlier test on Friday.
"We have the first BSE case in Germany, here in Schleswig-Holstein,"
Simonis said, referring to the scientific name of mad cow disease, bovine
spongiform encephalopathy (BSE).
The BSE cow was born in 1996 and slaughtered on 22 Nov 2000. The animal
was in a herd of 160 in Schleswig-Holstein, all of which are to be
slaughtered. A second cow exported from the eastern state of
Saxony-Anhalt to Portugal also tested positive.
"I have no idea how this could have happened," farmer Peter Lorenzen
said. "I don't think this is only my problem. A lot of farmers are
having the problem. They feed their cows the exact same way I do."
Butchers reported plunging beef sales amid calls for the resignation of
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's farm and health ministers following news
at least 2, and perhaps dozens more, of the country's 15 million cows
might be infected.
In an interview on Monday, European Health Commissioner David Byrne said
German authorities "did not want to believe it possible" that BSE could
be present there. They were "very complacent" he said. "I knew it was
only a question of time" before the first case would surface.
The British government came under renewed pressure on Sunday to ban
imports of French beef, after reports of cases in France. Agriculture
Minister Nick Brown suggested there would be no such ban, saying the
disease should be addressed on a European Union basis. The disease was
first detected in Britain in the 1980s.
The German government, which resisted strict measures, reversed itself
and called for tests on cattle throughout the EU.
Agriculture Minister Karl-Heinz Funke, who last week was saying he was
"absolutely convinced" Germany was immune to BSE, on Friday demanded
fast national testing of slaughtered cattle. He later widened the call to
urge mandatory testing throughout the EU and on beef imported into the
EU.
State and federal ministers also agreed at a meeting in Bonn to back
Schroeder's call for an immediate ban on the import, export and use of
animal feeds containing meat and bonemeal.
The measure will become law on Wednesday, and Germany will push for an
EU-wide ban in December. Infected feeds have been blamed for the spread
of BSE and the human form of mad cow disease, new variant
Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (nvCJD).
Butchers complained the announcement of BSE virtually halted all beef
sales.
A Dutch scientist and member of the EU's veterinary committee, Albert
Osterhaus, said he estimated there might be several dozen German cows
infected with BSE.
