[4
Date: 27 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com
Source: Reuters, 27 Nov 2000 [edited

The spread of BSE to Germany shows the brain-wasting sickness, which is
also deadly to people, knows no national frontiers, European Health
Commissioner David Byrne said.
Speaking on German television Byrne said it was a mistake to believe
German tests and controls were sufficient to keep out BSE. He also called
for transparency to restore consumer confidence.
"Germany long had the view there could be no cases of BSE. That was wrong
and I wasn't surprised... We need transparency. It's important consumers
know hey're getting all the information available and won't be fooled."
*******
[5
Date: 24 Nov 2000
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com and Saraiva da Cunha
<saraivainf@mail.telepac.pt>
Source: Reuters, 24 Nov 2000 [edited
<http://abcnews.go.com/wire/World/reuters20001124_405.html>

Azores islands report first mad cow case
----------------------------------------
LISBON - Portugal has detected the first case of BSE in the Azores, a
region exempted from a European Union ban on Portuguese beef exports, the
Agriculture Ministry said. The Ministry added the Fresian cow stricken by
the disease had been imported 2 years ago to the island of Sao Miguel from
Germany, where it was born in September 1995. The cow was slaughtered on 2
Oct 2000 and the carcass destroyed immediately on presenting signs of BSE.
Local Authorities in Azores announced a radical plan to slaughter all the
imported animals (about 2000 cows).
Veterinary authorities have placed the farm under embargo and informed
their counterparts in Germany. Portugal has repeatedly protested the EU
embargo is unfair because it has stricter measures to control BSE than many
other European countries.
The Ministry says the incidence of BSE in Portugal currently stands at 200
per million, down from 240 tallied in the 12 months to September 1999, and
is on course to be eradicated by 2003.
